{[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \HK. From \HKQJ65 the king is top of a strong sequence, and against notrump you attack your longest, strongest suit to set up the small hearts.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
We are in 3\N. Cashing tricks: the \HA is one, \DAKQ are three, so four on top. The ninth comes from clubs — my \CKT opposite dummy's \CQJ875 sets up four tricks once the \CA is knocked out, and a spade gives the rest. The danger is hearts: I hold only one stopper, so if I take it too soon a long heart suit may run when East gets in with the \CA.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West led the \HK, top of a sequence, so West almost certainly holds the \HQJ and a long suit — likely five or six hearts. I have only the \HA. By the Rule of Seven — subtract the six hearts you and dummy hold together from seven — hold up just once: duck the first round and win the \HA on the second. East holds only two hearts, so that single duck strips East of the suit. Then drive out the \CA; East wins but, with no heart left, cannot return it. Then my four clubs, three diamonds, the \HA and a spade bring it to nine.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
The hold-up was everything: the single duck stripped East's two hearts, so when East took the \CA there was no heart to return and West's suit was dead. Counting your winners first told you clubs, not hearts, was the source of the ninth trick. Nicely judged.}
