{[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \H7. From \HKQ8743 that is fourth-best of my longest, strongest suit against notrump, keeping the \HKQ on top to cash later.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
We play 3\N. On top I have \SAK (two), the \HA, \DA and \CAK — seven winners. The extra tricks come from spades: \SAK973 opposite \SJ65 develops to four once the suit behaves, giving the ninth. My problem is hearts: a single stopper, so I must hold up to cut the defenders' communication before conceding a spade.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West led the \H7, which looks like fourth-best, suggesting a five- or six-card suit headed by the \HKQ. With only the \HA I duck the first heart, and duck again if they continue, taking the ace on the third round to strip East of the suit. Then I play on spades from the top; even if I must concede one, the defender who wins will have no heart to return. Two spades become four, joining the \HA, \DA and \CAK for nine.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
Holding up the \HA until the third round was the key — it left the danger hand with no heart to lead when spades were forced out. Reading the fourth-best lead as a long suit warned you to duck rather than grab the ace. Well played.}
