{[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \H7. With \HKQ873 you have a good five-card suit without a third honor in sequence, so lead fourth-best from your longest suit.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
3\N. Three top \S, the \HA, a diamond, and a club give six. The development suit is \C, where \CAT863 opposite \CQ4 sets up four tricks once the \CK is dislodged — exactly the ninth and more. The \HA is my only heart stopper, so I must hold up before conceding the lead in clubs.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West led the \H7, which looks like a fourth-best, suggesting about five hearts to honors. If I win and then attack clubs, a long-heart defender would run the suit. So I duck twice and take the \HA on the third round, clearing East's hearts. Then I lead \C, forcing out the \CK; the clubs supply four tricks and East, if winning the \CK, has no heart to return. Four \C, three \S, the \HA, and a diamond make nine.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
The two-round hold-up was the whole hand: it left East safely on lead when the \CK was knocked out. Developing the club length finished the job. Nicely played.}
