{[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \H7. From \HKQ976 that is fourth-best of my longest, strongest suit against notrump, keeping the \HKQ on top to cash later.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
We are in 3\N. On top I have four diamonds from \DAJ73 opposite \DKQ5 and the \HA — five winners. The ninth comes from clubs, the development suit, where \CKQT32 opposite \CJ9 builds to four once the \CA is forced out. We hold 26 of the 40 points, so the defence has only 14; and since neither opponent bid, no one is hiding a long suit or a big hand, so the missing honours rate to split. My worry is hearts: a single stopper, so I must hold up before I let the defence in.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West led the \H7, which looks like a fourth-best, suggesting about a five-card suit headed by the \HKQ. Count the hearts you and dummy share — six — and subtract from seven: hold up once, ducking the first round and winning the \HA on the second to strip the short hand. By the rule of eleven, one card higher than the seven sits with East, so East rates to be the short hand and West to hold the long hearts. Then I drive out the \CA; whoever wins rates to be East, who will have no heart to return. Four clubs, four diamonds and the \HA make nine.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
The single duck was the key — it stripped the short hand of hearts, so knocking out the \CA was safe and West's suit was dead. Counting your winners told you clubs, not hearts, were the source of the ninth trick. Nicely judged.}
