{[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \HK. From \HKQT9863 the king is top of a strong sequence, the standard attack on the long heart suit I jumped to 3\H to show.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
We are in 3\N after West's 3\H jump overcall. That bid shows a long, weak heart suit — six or seven hearts — so West is the danger hand with the running suit, and East rates to hold at most one or two hearts. NS hold 25 of the 40 points, so the defence has 15 between them, most of it sitting with West's long suit. On top I have two spades from \SAK32, the \HA, and two top diamonds off \DAK74. The ninth comes from clubs, the development suit, building \CKJ2 opposite \CQ753 once the \CA is forced out. With only the lone \HA I must hold up to cut West off from his hearts.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West led the \HK from the suit he jumped in, confirming the long hearts sit with West, so East rates to be short — likely a singleton or doubleton. Win the \HA on the round that exhausts East of hearts: with East so short, ducking once and taking the ace on the second round rates to leave East bare. Then I force out the \CA to develop clubs; whoever wins rates to be East, who, with no heart to lead, cannot put West in to cash the long suit. Two top spades, the \HA and two top diamonds give five on top, and developing the clubs once the \CA is forced out brings the total to nine.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
Holding up the \HA until East's hearts were gone was everything — once East could not lead a heart, West's long suit was dead behind the lone stopper. Reading the 3\H overcall told you which hand held the danger and which was safe to lose the lead to. Good discipline.}
