{[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \HK. From \HKQT83 the king is top of a strong broken sequence (\HKQT), and against notrump you attack your longest, strongest suit to set up the small hearts.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
We are in 3\N. On top I have two spades, the \HA, a top diamond and two clubs — six winners. The ninth comes from spades: my \SAK543 opposite dummy's \SJT7 develops to four tricks, and a third club fills the gap. NS hold 28 of the 40, so the defence has only 12 between them; neither opponent bid, so no one hides a long suit or a big hand, and the missing honours rate to split. The danger is hearts: I hold only the \HA, so if I take it too soon a long heart suit may run when the defence gets in.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West led the \HK, which looks like top of a sequence, so West probably holds the \HQ and length — likely five hearts. Between dummy's \HJ42 and my \HA7 I hold five hearts, so by the Rule of Seven (seven minus five) I duck the first two rounds and win the \HA on the third. East, with the shorter holding, rates to run out of hearts on that third round, leaving the danger hand with no card to lead back. Then I set up the spades for the extra tricks; whoever wins cannot reach West's hearts.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
Ducking twice was the whole hand — it stripped the short defender of hearts, so when the spade lead was conceded there was no heart to return and West's suit was dead. Counting your winners first told you spades, not hearts, was the source of the ninth trick. Nicely judged.}
